odicals against the political, educational, and psychological discourses of their time, Dafna Zur argues that the figure of the child was particularly favorable to the project of modernity and nation-building, as well as to the colonial and postcolonial projects of socialization and nationalization. She demonstrates the ways in which Korean children's literature builds on a trajectory that begins with the child as an organic part of nature, and ends, in the post-colonial era, with the child as the primary agent of control of nature. Figuring Korean Futures reveals the complex ways in which the figure of the child became a driving force of nostalgia that stood in for future aspirations for the individual, family, class, and nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aChildren's literature, KoreanxHistory and criticism. 0aChildren's periodicals, KoreanxHistoryx20th century. 0aChildren's periodicals, KoreanxHistoryy20th century. 0aKorean periodicalsxHistoryx20th century. 0aKorean periodicalsxHistoryy20th century. 4aKorea. 4achild-heart. 4achildren's literature. 4acolonialism. 4aliberation. 4amodernity. 4anation. 4anature. 4aperiodicals. 4ascience. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503603110zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503603110423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503603110.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles